</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Given a <fr:link
href="erct-001F.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001F">truncation level</fr:link> <fr:tex>n</fr:tex>, we define what it means for a type to be <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> by induction:</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li>a type is <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>-2</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> when it is <fr:link
href="erct-001H.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001H">contractible</fr:link>;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>a type is <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>-1</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> when it is a <fr:link
href="erct-001I.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001I">proposition</fr:link>;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>for <fr:tex>n  \geq  0</fr:tex>, a type <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> when for every <fr:tex>x,y:A</fr:tex> the identification type <fr:tex>x=y</fr:tex> is <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n-1</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span>.</fr:li></fr:ul><fr:p>So, in particular, a <fr:tex>0</fr:tex>-truncated type is precisely a <fr:em>set</fr:em>. We shall often refer to <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n</fr:tex>-truncated</html:span> types as <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>n</fr:tex>-types</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
